 "text": "Where are the two independent packet traces, if you traced on both client and server at the same time?\n\nAlso, disabling SACK will lead to much worst packet loss recovery performance, while also prevent TSO / LRO issues simulatanouely.\n\nA SACK enabled, LRO/TSO disabled test would be interesting.\n\n\n\nI asked awk to create a simple 32bit sum of the 1448-byte payload segments making up the LRO chunks, for all the data segments with an even multiple:\n\n(sum32 is not perfect, but should be sufficient to see identical sub-sections; note that prior to the capture, the packets  appear to have been sent before, which are in frame #4 - #21.\n\nthe first 1448byte chunk in #63 is identical to #66, indicating this could be an off-by-one mbuf issue. All duplicate, subsequently seen chunks are prefixed with # below.\n\n\npacket #63 should have many overlaps with packets #55 and #57 - but they do NOT correspond properly...\n\n3rd chunk of #63 should be 1st chunk of #55, but only chunks 4 and 2 (and following) are the same, similar between #63/13 and #57/1, where only subsequent chunks are the same...\n\n\nframe.number ip.src tcp.seq(rel) tcp.ack(rel) tcp.len #_1448_segs\n[sum32 sum32...]\n\n\n2 10.234.1.9 35249 229 15928 11\n72053392291     385714934591    419632206729    401031568921    410043220839    398170924830    381008236919    388657879560    400554947764    390059647829 401051361480\n\n4 10.234.1.9 8689 229 1448 1\n402468043721\n5 10.234.1.9 10137 229 1448 1\n401277757279\n6 10.234.1.9 11585 229 1448 1\n415282924207\n7 10.234.1.9 13033 229 1448 1\n384078634026\n8 10.234.1.9 14481 229 1448 1\n403972324660\n9 10.234.1.9 15929 229 1448 1\n406377582180\n10 10.234.1.9 17377 229 1448 1\n395849724237\n11 10.234.1.9 18825 229 1448 1\n407105644009\n12 10.234.1.9 20273 229 1448 1\n391049306449\n13 10.234.1.9 21721 229 1448 1\n392972187658\n14 10.234.1.9 23169 229 1448 1\n412806674913\n15 10.234.1.9 24617 229 1448 1\n368815440121\n16 10.234.1.9 26065 229 1448 1\n4414